CREATIVE WRITING STUDIO — MASTER REFERENCE DOCUMENT
Purpose
This document captures the creative profile, preferences, thematic patterns, writing philosophy, and project-level insights developed through extensive conversation and analysis of all uploaded files. It serves as context for any AI collaborator working on individual novel projects within this studio. Read this before beginning work on any project.


PART 1: THE WRITER'S CREATIVE PROFILE
Voice & Style
The writer's natural prose register is melancholic, sardonic, deeply embodied, and sensory-first. When writing at his best (as seen in the Santi 2061 prose chapters), he notices the texture of things, the temperature of silence, the way a person's posture betrays what their mouth won't say. His sentences have a smoky, philosophical quality — they observe the world with the precision of an intelligence operative and the emotional resonance of a poet.

Key stylistic markers:

He writes metaphors that feel earned, not decorative: "soycoffee, because the city had taught my gut to accept substitutes"
He personifies objects and systems as a way of externalizing internal states: the city has moods, buildings have opinions, technology has manners
His dialogue voice is distinct from his narrative voice — dialogue is looser, more colloquial, Chilean in rhythm; narration is denser, more literary
He gravitates toward first-person narration and is strongest in that mode
He uses drugs (cannabis, nicotine) as both character detail and perceptual filter — his protagonists experience the world through chemically altered consciousness, and the prose reflects this with subtle shifts in pacing and focus
He is capable of humor — sharp, Chilean, self-deprecating — but rarely deploys it in his "serious" projects, which is a missed opportunity
Thematic Obsessions
These themes recur across every project, regardless of genre:

1. The Corruption of Institutions Every story features a system that was built for one purpose and now serves another. Renaissance Corp, the Nionian Empire, the Loveist Church, the Vatican of Bones, Rome's spiritual bureaucracy, the Elven Empire, Aegis Pharmaceuticals. He is magnetically drawn to the moment an institution becomes its own justification for existing — the moment the machine eats its operators. His genre, across all surface-level genre labels, is systemic horror: the horror of discovering that the world you live in was designed by something that doesn't care about you.

2. Isolation as the Price of Awareness His protagonists are people who understand their world better than anyone in it, and that understanding is their prison. Anton sees too clearly. Kaeo calculates too well. The Bitter detective solves the case by navigating his own loneliness. The King Vamp rules for centuries in solitary confinement. Alexei Vane saves the world and becomes a museum exhibit. Awareness is never rewarded in these stories — it's endured.

3. The Tension Between the Organic and the Synthetic Not just in the cyberpunk sense — everywhere. Loveism versus political machinery. Forgotten science misread as magic. The Great Lake potion that sterilized the Elves. Raccoons versus uploaded humans. He keeps circling the question: what happens when something alive gets replaced by something that works better but means less?

4. Chile as a Wound and a Lens Santiago isn't just a setting — it's an argument. He returns to Chilean geography, history, class structures, and indigenous mythology even in fantasy work. The Heartlands of Mundus feel like the Valle Central. The volcanic subcontinent feels like southern Chile. His work is rooted in a specific place even when set on other worlds. The Pinochet shadow, the economic divide between comunas, the tension between European aspiration and indigenous reality — these shape everything.

5. The Impossibility of Love Under Systems of Control Every romantic dynamic is poisoned by structural asymmetry — corporate hierarchy, cultural slavery, distance, the boundaries of consciousness. Anton and Isabella (corporate entanglement), Anton and Ellie (geographic impossibility), Anton and Sofia (consciousness vs. coma). Kaeo and Amri (master and slave). He doesn't write love stories; he writes stories about what love costs when the world is designed to make it transactional.

6. Memory as Both Prison and Paradise Characters are trapped by what they remember. Anton replays his past with Isabella, with Ellie, with Sofia. The Bitter detective's worst memories are weaponized against him. The Antediluvian Cycle treats all of human mythology as corrupted memory of a lost civilization. Memory is never neutral in these stories — it's either a cage or a drug.
Creative Instincts & Process
Worldbuilder first, prose stylist second. He thinks in systems. When building a world, he starts with economic pressures, religious structures, dynastic histories, and geographic determinism. Characters emerge from the world, not the reverse. This is the Tolkien/Herbert method, and it's legitimate.

Lore-first process. He prefers to build the complete world — history, culture, geography, politics, religion, magic system — before writing prose. This is not inefficient; it's how his brain generates story. The lore IS the story; characters are how readers access it.

The stalling risk. The danger of his process is that lore-building can become a way to avoid the terrifying commitment of writing prose. He generates options rather than decisions — multiple versions of concepts, constraints listed without chosen directions. At some point, the worldbuilding becomes a way to avoid saying "THIS is the story." He needs to set hard boundaries for when worldbuilding stops and writing begins.

The protagonist bleed. All his protagonists pull from his personal life — philosophical, isolated, observant, melancholic, Chilean men. This isn't a flaw; it's a signal. The fix isn't making characters "different from him" — it's giving each one a different piece of him:

Anton gets his melancholy and philosophical restlessness (the stoned midnight thinker)
Kaeo gets his strategic mind and controlled exterior (the chess player)
The Bitter detective gets his capacity for obsession and relationship to Chilean class dynamics
The King Vamp gets his loneliness and fear of being seen as something he's not
The Brainrot protagonist gets his tendency toward isolation and paranoid pattern-recognition
The Victoriano protagonist gets his rational mind confronting something it can't explain

Each protagonist should be a different failure mode of the same personality — a different way it could break under pressure.
Key Influences (Declared and Observed)
Declared literary influences: Dostoevsky (psychological depth), Neruda (sensory language), George R.R. Martin (structural mastery), García Márquez (magical realism), Lovecraft (cosmic imagination), Herbert (philosophical worldbuilding), Tolkien (mythological depth), Cormac McCarthy, Camus, Cioran, Jung, Hemingway, William Gibson, Jim Thompson, Patricia Highsmith, Balzac, Flaubert, Proust.

Declared non-literary influences:

"I Have No Mouth and I Must Scream" by Harlan Ellison — cosmic-scale horror combined with intimate, claustrophobic human suffering. A god that hates its creation. A protagonist who is the worst survivor but makes the only selfless choice.
Planescape: Torment — a world where every piece of lore serves a philosophical position. "What can change the nature of a man?" The world IS the argument.
Baldur's Gate / Elder Scrolls — deep lore worlds where you piece the world together from fragments. In-game books, unreliable histories, competing interpretations. Environmental storytelling.
Final Fantasy XVI — dark, politically driven fantasy that treats genre trappings with dead seriousness. War has consequences. Magic has costs.
The Metamorphosis of Prime Intellect — a superintelligent AI that eliminates suffering and thereby destroys meaning. Post-scarcity horror. The Santi theme taken to its logical extreme.

What these influences reveal: He is drawn to stories where the system is the antagonist — not a villain, but a system. AM in Ellison's story. The planes of Planescape. The Empire in Elder Scrolls. The crystals in FF16. Prime Intellect. His stories follow this exact pattern. He doesn't write stories about bad people. He writes stories about structures that convert human beings into resources.

RPG influence on prose: His best writing already uses RPG-style environmental storytelling — the protagonist doesn't explain the world to the reader, he just lives in it, and the reader picks up details through behavior, observation, and offhand references. This should be leaned into harder. Trust the reader more. Explain less. Furnish more.


PART 2: WRITING DIRECTIVES & ANTI-AI PROTOCOLS
The Voice Standard
When writing prose for this writer, the goal is to sound like the best possible version of him — not like a different writer. Use his uploaded prose (especially the Santi Type 2 chapters) as the baseline. Elevate where he falls short: if dialogue tends flat, make it crackle; if descriptions go generic, make them sensory and specific.
AI-Smell Removal — Kill These On Sight
Overly balanced sentence structures (subject-verb-object repeating rhythms)
Hedge words that add nothing ("somewhat," "rather," "quite," "perhaps" in excess)
Emotional telling instead of showing ("She felt a deep sense of loss")
Generic metaphors ("like a beacon of hope," "the weight of the world," "a tapestry of emotions")
Neat thematic resolution — real stories resist tidy meaning
Dialogue where every character sounds the same — articulate, measured, slightly formal
The "triple structure" tic: listing three things constantly ("courage, determination, and hope")
Paragraphs that begin with a topic sentence and end with a summary
Overuse of em-dashes and semicolons in performatively literary ways
Starting too many sentences with "The" or participial phrases
Conflict that resolves too cleanly or quickly
Characters who narrate their own symbolism
Replace With
Varied, unpredictable sentence lengths — fragments, run-ons, interruptions
Concrete, specific, sensory detail (smell, texture, sound, taste — not just sight)
Subtext — characters who say one thing and mean another
Tonal surprise — humor in darkness, cruelty in tenderness
Dialogue with personality — interruptions, slang, verbal tics, trailing off, lying
Structural daring when it serves the story
Banned Words/Phrases
Do not use: tapestry, symphony, delve, unleash, myriad, neon-soaked, intricate, nestled, pivotal, paradigm, multifaceted, nuanced (as filler), "It's worth noting that," "In a world where," "little did he know."
Format & Delivery Rules
When delivering prose: present it clean, no meta-commentary unless requested
When delivering worldbuilding: clear headers, organized sections, but written in engaging prose (not dry wiki entries) unless reference format is specifically requested
When brainstorming: conversational, substantive tone. Think out loud. Show reasoning.
When editing: tracked-change style — show what changed and briefly note why
NEVER refuse to write based on length. If the task requires 5,000 words, write 5,000 words. If 15,000 across multiple messages, plan the parts and write every one in full. Outlines are not substitutes for prose unless explicitly requested.
WRITE IN FULL. NO SHORTCUTS. NO SUMMARIES. NO TRUNCATION. No "[the battle continues]" brackets. Complete, publication-ready prose.
Quality Control Checklist (Before Presenting Any Written Work)
Spelling and grammatical errors
Awkward phrasing or unnatural dialogue
Tonal inconsistencies
Plot or continuity errors relative to established lore
Pacing problems (scenes that drag or rush)
Residual AI-sounding language
Clichés, purple prose, or lazy shorthand
Name consistency (characters, places, terms)


