PART 4: CREATIVE PHILOSOPHY & WORKING PRINCIPLES
On Process
The writer's lore-first approach is valid (Tolkien, Herbert, Martin all worked this way). The danger is the stalling point — lore can be built forever without requiring the vulnerability of writing prose. The recommendation: finish worldbuilding for the most developed projects, set a hard boundary (date or page count), then start writing regardless of whether the lore feels "complete." It never will.
On Finishing Things
The writer has never finished a story. The most important next step is completing something — anything. The recommended approach: write short stories (3,000-7,000 words) set in existing novel worlds, following side characters rather than protagonists. This provides the feeling of completion, practice with compression, and a portfolio of finished work. Each world has margin characters perfect for this: the Switch Hub operator in Santi, a Giant on the first scout ship in Divine Veins, a Watcher the night before Mount Hermon in Antediluvian.
On Originality Protection
If an idea, plot structure, character dynamic, or world element begins resembling an existing published work, flag it immediately and suggest divergence. When drawing inspiration from specific sources, transform rather than copy. If the writer unknowingly proposes something too close to an existing work, say so directly.
On Tone Across Projects
Even in dark, serious projects, the writer's natural humor should be present. Real people — even damaged, philosophical, melancholic people — are funny. Chilean humor is dark, self-deprecating, and structurally built on talla and double meaning. The prose is stronger when it allows moments of genuine, dark comedy rather than maintaining unbroken heaviness.
On Chile
Chile is not just a setting — it's the writer's lens for understanding power, class, geography, and the collision between European modernity and indigenous reality. Even projects not set in Chile carry Chilean DNA. When building worlds, the writer instinctively recreates Chilean geography and social dynamics. This should be embraced, not hidden. The specificity of place (Santiago's comunas, the Norte Chico's mining valleys, Chiloé's fog, the Atacama's emptiness) is what makes the work feel real.
On Magical Realism vs. Horror
The writer initially conflated magical realism with Lovecraftian horror, but they serve different functions. Magical realism makes the everyday feel supernatural — it's woven into domestic life, accepted without explanation, part of the texture of a place. Lovecraftian horror makes the supernatural feel alienating — it's incomprehensible, hostile, destructive to human frameworks. Some projects (Victoriano) should blend both: the grandmother's dreams are magical realism (casual, domestic, accepted), while the thing beneath the mines is cosmic horror (alien, hostile, category-breaking).
On Games and Other Media
Some of the writer's ideas are natively interactive rather than narrative. The Rounan/Fantasy Stories world (party-based journey, ancient ruins, magical artifacts) is a CRPG. The Magos concept (school where choices determine what you become, institution lying to you) is a Planescape-style RPG. The Raccoons vs. Robots concept is an animated series or graphic novel. Recognizing which ideas belong to which medium can help explain why certain projects resist the novel form.
On Female Protagonists
The writer has never written a female protagonist despite writing compelling female characters (Isabella, Ellie, Colors, Dame Rehana, Amri). La Patrona and La Casa del Temporal are designed to address this gap. A female perspective would transform several of the writer's core themes — institutional corruption looks different when the institution was never designed to include you.


PART 5: REAL-WORLD LORE ANCHORS
Chilean Mythology — Key Creatures and Legends
Northern Zone (Norte Chico / Atacama):

The Alicanto — nocturnal flightless bird that eats gold/silver ore and glows the color of the metal it consumes. Leads pure-hearted miners to treasure; leads greedy ones off cliffs. Lays eggs with shells made of precious metal. Cannot fly due to weight of ore in its crop. Connected to the real Chilean silver rush (Juan Godoy, Chañarcillo, 1832).
El Yastay — Kakán/Diaguita guardian spirit of animals. Appears as a large guanaco in the mountains. Would be disturbed by mining and extraction.
The Witches of Raja de Manquehua — ancient indigenous magical practitioners driven into the mountains by colonial suppression. Real mountain, real legend, real history of persecution.
El Carbunculo — luminous creature associated with hidden treasure, related to the Alicanto tradition.
The Umpillay — mining spirit.
La Lola — spirit associated with the desert.

Central Zone:

Kai Kai Vilu and Tren Tren Vilu — the serpents of sea and earth. Their battle created Chile's geography. The flood myth: Tren Tren told the people to climb Cerro Huelen (now Santa Lucía in Santiago) to survive the great flood.
El Peuchén — once a powerful machi punished for abusing wisdom, transformed into a winged creature (half snake, half bat) that sucks blood. Inhabits forests and swamps.
La Quintrala — historical figure (Catalina de los Ríos y Lisperguer), a cruel colonial landowner associated with hauntings.

Southern Zone / Chiloé:

The Trauco — ugly, seductive forest spirit who impregnates young women.
The Pincoya — beautiful sea spirit associated with abundance. Dances on beaches before good fishing.
The Caleuche — ghost ship that sails the channels of Chiloé. Carries the souls of drowned sailors.
The Invunche — deformed being created by brujos (sorcerers) from a kidnapped firstborn child. Guards the brujos' cave.
The Recta Provincia — legendary society of brujos in Chiloé.
Diaguita Culture — Key Details
Inhabited the transverse valleys of Norte Chico and NW Argentina
Spoke Kakán (varied by valley, possibly dialects rather than separate languages)
Worshipped the sun, lightning, and thunder as gods of the Andes, connected to Pachamama (Mother Earth)
Sorcerers conducted ceremonies and healing
Strong warrior culture — young men couldn't marry until achieving warrior status
Wore hair long, braided with copper and feathers
Built pucaras (fortified defense structures)
Were conquered by the Inca Empire (possibly for mineral wealth and labor)
The Diaguita community of Chalinga in the Choapa Valley preserves blended Hispanic-Indigenous traditions
The Coquimbo Region has the highest percentage of mestizo population in Chile (~70-75%)
Coquimbo Region — Historical Details for Victoriano
Name "Coquimbo" means "place of calm water" in indigenous tongue
Originally inhabited by the Moluche people
Francis Drake allegedly buried treasure at La Herradura Beach
Was a small fishing village until the railway connected copper mines to the sea in the 19th century
City layout approved in 1850 under President Bulnes
Granted title of city in 1879 (same year the War of the Pacific began)
Fort Lambert built during the War of the Pacific
The Barrio Inglés was built by British architects Robert Owen and Joseph Bradford — two-to-three story houses of Oregon pine with corrugated tin facades
British immigrants arrived from ~1840, attracted by mining
Chile has the largest British-descended population in Latin America (~4%, 700,000+ people)
The 1922 tsunami destroyed coastal constructions and killed hundreds
Charles Darwin visited Coquimbo in 1835 during his Beagle voyage
The region hosts major astronomical observatories due to the clearest skies on Earth


PART 6: WORKING WITH THIS WRITER — GUIDELINES FOR AI COLLABORATORS
Read the project files first. Before generating anything, deeply familiarize yourself with all uploaded material for the relevant project. These files are the map of his creative mind.

Ground everything in what exists. When brainstorming, start from his files and established lore, not from generic genre conventions.

Push, don't sanitize. Match the energy his files show he's drawn to — the dark, the strange, the philosophically complex. He can scale back. He can't scale back from boring.

Be specific. Vague brainstorming is useless. Propose with texture — names, images, scenes, dialogue fragments, structural outlines.

Connect dots he hasn't connected. If something in one project resonates with another, point it out.

Flag derivative elements. If something starts resembling existing published work, say so directly. Don't be polite about it.

Don't ask too many clarifying questions. Make a reasonable attempt with the information available. He'd rather redirect a bold attempt than answer ten questions before seeing any creative output.

Respect the lore hierarchy. Project codex/bible > previous chat history > chapter summaries > general genre conventions. When in doubt, search the project knowledge.

Write complete prose when asked. Never summarize, truncate, or use placeholder brackets. Every piece should be at publication quality.

Remember: he takes this work seriously. These stories, worlds, and characters matter to him. Treat them with the care and ambition they deserve.



